âš™ï¸ Slide 3 â€“ Mapping to Merton Logic (Expanded)

ğŸ§© A. What the Original Merton Model Does
	â€¢	A firmâ€™s assets follow a stochastic process A_t that fluctuates with market volatility Ïƒâ‚.
	â€¢	It has debt D, a fixed obligation due at maturity T.
	â€¢	If at T the assets are worth less than the debt (A_T < D), the firm defaults.
	â€¢	Because both assets and debt move stochastically, we can quantify how often that happens in probabilistic terms.
	â€¢	The distance to default is
d_2 = \frac{\ln(A_0 / D) + (r - 0.5Ïƒ_A^2) T}{Ïƒ_A âˆšT}
and
PD = N(-d_2).
	â€¢	In plain English: the closer and more volatile the firmâ€™s assets are relative to its debt, the higher the chance the debt will overtake the assets before maturity.

â¸»

ğŸ’§ B. Why This Applies to Hedge Funds

As the Liquidity Buffer Burnout paper notes, a depleting margin account is mathematically equivalent to an asset process hitting a debt barrier â€” a first-passage (default) model in the sense of Merton (1974) and Black & Cox (1976) ï¿¼.

Merton Model	Hedge-Fund Liquidity Model	Intuition
Assets Aâ‚œ	Liquidity buffer B(t)	Cash available to meet margin calls
Debt D	Cumulative margin calls C(t)	Cash demanded by brokers
Default event: Aâ‚œ < D	Default event: B(t) depleted â†’ C(t) > B(0)	Buffer runs out
Volatility Ïƒâ‚	Volatility of loss Ïƒâ‚• (from stress or IA ratio)	Market uncertainty drives both
Horizon T (1 yr)	MPR h (â‰ˆ 10 days)	Reaction time window

Thus, the hedge-fund default probability can be written analogously as
PD_h = 1 - Î¦\!\left(\frac{B - m h}{Ïƒ_h}\right),
the short-horizon version of Mertonâ€™s PD = N(-d_2).

